Main Topic: Docker Compose
Introduction & Purpose:
Docker Compose is a tool for automating multi-container deployments using declarative YAML files
Eliminates the need to repeatedly run manual docker run commands with multiple options
Files can be version-controlled and shared with team members for consistent environment setup
Docker Compose File Structure (docker-compose.yml):
Networks Section:
Creates custom bridge networks automatically
Containers in the same network can communicate via container names (not IP addresses)
Syntax: networks: followed by network name
Volumes Section:
Creates named volumes for data persistence
Syntax: volumes: followed by volume name
Volumes are stored in /var/lib/docker/volumes
Services Section:
Defines containers/microservices to deploy
Each service includes:
image: - Docker image name
container_name: - Name for the container
ports: - Port mapping (host:container)
networks: - Network attachment
volumes: - Volume mapping
environment: - Environment variables
depends_on: - Service dependencies
restart: - Restart policy (always/never/on-failure)
build: - Build image from Dockerfile
Key Commands:
docker compose up -d - Create and start containers in detached mode
docker compose up --build - Build images and start containers
docker compose down - Stop and remove containers/networks
docker compose down -v - Also remove volumes
docker compose ps - List running containers
Environment Variables:
Can be hardcoded in YAML (not recommended for passwords)
Use .env file for sensitive data (not shared in version control)
Pass variables at runtime: VAR=value docker compose up -d
Reference in YAML using ${VARIABLE_NAME}
Practical Examples Demonstrated:
WordPress + MySQL deployment with networking and volumes
Node.js application with Dockerfile build integration
